Great, since you're on Windows 10 and want to keep everything private, I'll give you PowerShell commands you can run yourself.

**First, let's check the most common Bitcoin Core wallet location on your PC** (just in case it's still there):

Open **PowerShell as administrator** (right-click Start → Windows PowerShell (Admin)). Then run:

```powershell
# Check default Bitcoin Core wallet location
if (Test-Path "$env:APPDATA\Bitcoin\wallet.dat") {
    Write-Host "Found: $env:APPDATA\Bitcoin\wallet.dat"
} else {
    Write-Host "No wallet.dat in default AppData location."
}
```

**Now scan the external drive E:\** and your Documents folder. We'll search for any `.dat` files (since Bitcoin Core wallets are `.dat` files), and also check the first few bytes to confirm it's a Berkeley DB wallet (the format Bitcoin Core uses). Run this:

```powershell
# Create an empty list to hold results
$results = @()

# Scan E:\ (up to 3 folders deep to avoid huge scans)
Get-ChildItem -Path "E:\" -Recurse -Depth 3 -Include "*.dat" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | ForEach-Object {
    $file = $_
    try {
        $bytes = [System.IO.File]::ReadAllBytes($file.FullName)
        # Berkeley DB wallet.dat files start with hex 0x00000000 or 0x00010000, but often with "DB" (0x44 0x42) in first 2 bytes
        if ($bytes.Count -ge 2 -and $bytes[0] -eq 0x00 -and $bytes[1] -eq 0x00) {
            $results += $file.FullName
        } elseif ($bytes.Count -ge 2 -and $bytes[0] -eq 0x44 -and $bytes[1] -eq 0x42) {
            $results += $file.FullName
        }
    } catch {
        # skip files we can't read
    }
}

# Scan C:\Users\$env:USERNAME\Documents (up to 3 folders)
Get-ChildItem -Path "$env:USERPROFILE\Documents" -Recurse -Depth 3 -Include "*.dat" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | ForEach-Object {
    $file = $_
    try {
        $bytes = [System.IO.File]::ReadAllBytes($file.FullName)
        if ($bytes.Count -ge 2 -and $bytes[0] -eq 0x00 -and $bytes[1] -eq 0x00) {
            $results += $file.FullName
        } elseif ($bytes.Count -ge 2 -and $bytes[0] -eq 0x44 -and $bytes[1] -eq 0x42) {
            $results += $file.FullName
        }
    } catch {}
}

# Show results
if ($results.Count -gt 0) {
    Write-Host "`nFound potential wallet files (Content verified):"
    $results | ForEach-Object { Write-Host $_ }
} else {
    Write-Host "`nNo Bitcoin Core wallet files found in scanned areas."
    Write-Host "Tip: If the file was renamed (e.g., backup.dat), we can widen the search. Also check cloud sync folders."
}
```

This will **only** show you the file paths – it never prints the contents of the wallet.

**If nothing is found**, let me know and we can widen the search (maybe the file has a different extension, or it's inside a compressed backup archive). Also, do you recall if you ever used **Wallet Encryption** in Bitcoin Core? That might produce a different filename pattern.

Once you have the path(s), let me know and we'll move to the password recovery step.
